h returns nil).\n\nLet me look at one more potential issue: in the `runner.go` Execute method, when we restore baseCommands/baseExplicit/baseAgentArgs before each step, and there's a step-level agent_args sub-block that produces keys like `agent_args.mockagent`, these get parsed by `parseAgentArgsConfig(step.Config, \"agent_args.\")`. But the key `agent_args` (flat) also exists and is handled separately as `ExplicitArgs`. The prefix matching ensures `agent_args.mockagent` matches `\"agent_args.\"` but `agent_args` does NOT match `\"agent_args.\"` because `strings.TrimPrefix(\"agent_args\", \"agent_args.\")` returns the full string (since it doesn't have the prefix). Wait, let me check: `strings.HasPrefix(\"agent_args\", \"agent_args.\")` → `false` because `\"agent_args\"` is shorter than `\"agent_args.\"`. Correct.\n\nBut wait, there could be a subtle issue: if a step config has `agent_args.mockagent` AND `agent_args` (the flat one), `agent_args` is handled as `ExplicitArgs` in the runner, and `agent_args.mockagent` is handled as per-agent args. That's fine - the priority system in `argsFor` handles this correctly (ExplicitArgs takes priority).\n\nThe code looks correct. The implementation:\n1. DSL parser supports nested sub-blocks in both workflow-level config and step-level config\n2. `parseAgentArgsConfig` extracts per-agent overrides from config maps\n3. `argsFor` has a clear priority chain (ExplicitArgs > AgentArgs > defaults)\n4. Step overrides are properly restored to workflow defaults between steps\n5. Fallback chains work via comma-separated `agent_command`\n6. Tests cover all the new functionality\n\nThe only thing I should verify is that this code is consistent and actually compiles correctly. Let me do one more check on imports."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":285,"cache_read_input_tokens":77426,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":285},"output_token